	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />There seems to be a lot of interest in this, and a growing amount of hardware interest in this community.  I think it might be time to start a open source project to re-implement some of the NES's parts.  I would propose doing separate VHDL implementations of the APU, CPU and PPU on the NES, as well as some MMC chips.  It wouldn't be too hard to wire a CPLD or FPGA into a toaster or cart to try each of these out individually.  Once this foundation started to work, people could start putting them together into stand alone systems.  
<br />Kevin's FPGA NES doesn't make any sense to manufacture at this point in time - and neither would a system based on community designs.   However, the work can be done and tested now - and maybe by the time it's done there will be a more viable option to manufacture.  It will be fun and educational regardless of whether it ever turns into a product.  Plus, we can always test it out on demo boards like the one at Microsprite <a href="http://www.microsprite.com/documentation" class="postlink">http://www.microsprite.com/documentation</a>
<br />This idea gives us nice options... like adding s-video out to the PPU.  Sure, it won't be any better quality, but at least your more modern cables will fit in it.
<br />If anyone would like to pursue this, please register your interest.  I've got a start on a MMC1 implementation to kick things off - it's pretty rough right now but you have to start somewhere <img src="./images/smilies/icon_biggrin.gif" alt=":D" title="Very Happy" />  I also know a bit about microprocessor design, so I don't think re-implementing a 6502 will be that tough.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


